article.description: Tina Thompson scored 24 points to lead the Comets to a 75-71 victory over the Sparks on Saturday.
article.headline: Leslie notches double-double in loss
article.linkText: Comets edge Sparks to snap two-game skid
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Trailing by 13 in the fourth quarter, the Houston
Comets didn't panic.

"We just came out in the second half knowing that we had to be
efficient on defense to get the job done," Comets forward Tina
Thompson said. "We were able to hit some tough shots and close it
out in the end."

Thompson scored 24 points and Sheryl Swoopes had her first
double-double of the season, leading Houston to a 75-71 victory
over the Los Angeles Sparks to end its two-game losing streak.

It was Los Angeles' second loss in a row.

The Comets were down 13 with 7:09 left when they went on a 15-2
run. They took their first lead of the game on Thompson's layup
with 2:24 left.

Swoopes helped extend the lead by making a layup and a pair of
free throws with under two minutes to play.

The Sparks got within three when Tamecka Dixon made a layup with
11 seconds left, but Michelle Snow made a free throw for the final
margin.

Lisa Leslie scored a team-high 18 points for Los Angeles and
added 12 rebounds for her third double-double of the season.

"For us to be able to come back with three minutes to go and
being down by nine and pull out a win, I think that says a lot
about the character of this team and the talent of this team,"
Swoopes said.

Los Angeles made just two shots in the final 5:22 and lost
back-to-back games for the first time this season.

"I thought we played well in both halves, but we just had a bad
lapse in the last five minutes of the game," Leslie said. "We
took some bad shots and committed some silly fouls that really hurt
us. The momentum just switched from there."

After DeLisha Milton-Jones hit a jump shot to make it 69-60 with
5:22 left, Kedra Holland-Cord started Houston's decisive run by
making four consecutive free throws.

The Comets, who ended the game with a 20-4 spurt, got six points
down the stretch from Swoopes.

She finished with 10 points and 10 rebounds. Mwadi Mabika added
10 points in the first half.
